solution: First, we note  \[x^3-y^3 = (x-y)(x^2 +xy +y^2) = 6(24+xy),\] so we just need to find $xy$ now.  Squaring both sides of $x-y=6$ gives  $$x^2 - 2xy + y^2 = 36.$$ Since $x^2 + y^2 = 24$, we have $24-2xy = 36$, so $xy = -6$, from which we have  \[x^3-y^3 = 6(24 +xy) = 6(24 - 6) = 6(18) = \boxed{108}.\]

\begin{align*}
x^3-y^3&=(x-y)(x^2+xy+y^2)\\
&=(6)(x^2+y^2+xy)\\
&=72+6xy.
\end{align*}Next, we can easily solve the system $x-y=6$ and $x^2+y^2=24$ via trigonometry or some other methods. In this case, I'll give an outline of the solution. Solve $x-y=6$ for $y$ in terms of $x$ to get $y=x-6$, and then square both sides of the equation to get
$$(x-6)^2=x^2-12x+36.$$Expanding the left-hand side, we then have
$$x^2-12x+36=x^2+36-12x=\left(36-12x\right),$$which means that $x^2=12$, so $x=\pm2\sqrt{3}$. We substitute our values of $x$ back into $y=x-6$ and find that $y=\pm4\sqrt{3}-6$, and so, for example, if $x=2\sqrt{3}$, then $y=-2\sqrt{3}-6$. Finally, we calculate
$$48+24=\boxed{72}.$$So $x^3-y^3=(x-y)(x^2+y^2+xy)=(6)(72+6xy)=6\left(72+(6)(12\sqrt{3})\right)=\boxed{486}$$.
